To run this scenario on bare metal:

 1. Set your bare-metal build tree to the state shown in this file:
    /tmp/tmp.XbaKbm3Dnb/tools/testing/selftests/rcutorture/res/2022.12.18-03.30.15/testid.txt
 2. Update your bare-metal build tree's .config based on this file:
    /tmp/tmp.XbaKbm3Dnb/tools/testing/selftests/rcutorture/res/2022.12.18-03.30.15/SRCU-N/ConfigFragment
 3. Make the bare-metal kernel's build system aware of your .config updates:
    $ yes "" | make oldconfig
 4. Build your bare-metal kernel.
 5. Boot your bare-metal kernel with the following parameters:
   
 6. Start the test with the following command:
    $ modprobe rcutorture torture_type=srcu fwd_progress=3 onoff_interval=1000 onoff_holdoff=30 n_barrier_cbs=4 stat_interval=15 shutdown_secs=21600 test_no_idle_hz=1 verbose=1
 7. After some time, end the test with the following command:
    $ rmmod rcutorture
 8. Copy your bare-metal kernel's .config file, overwriting this file:
    /tmp/tmp.XbaKbm3Dnb/tools/testing/selftests/rcutorture/res/2022.12.18-03.30.15/SRCU-N/.config
 9. Copy the console output from just before the modprobe to just after
    the rmmod into this file:
    /tmp/tmp.XbaKbm3Dnb/tools/testing/selftests/rcutorture/res/2022.12.18-03.30.15/SRCU-N/console.log
10. Check for runtime errors using the following command:
    $ tools/testing/selftests/rcutorture/bin/kvm-recheck.sh /tmp/tmp.XbaKbm3Dnb/tools/testing/selftests/rcutorture/res/2022.12.18-03.30.15

Some of the above steps may be skipped if you build your bare-metal
kernel here: /tmp/tmp.XbaKbm3Dnb
